The paper focuses on developing a planner for robots to reach objects in cluttered environments, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The approach involves learning from human demonstrations and using classifiers to generate a high-level plan, which involves artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The use of virtual reality to generate data and the segmentation of human demonstrations suggest a focus on human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Finally, the paper mentions the use of computer vision techniques to generate a qualitative representation of the task space, which suggests a possible connection to computer vision (cs.CV).
